🚀 30 Days DSA Pattern Challenge – Day 4

Continuing my journey of learning DSA through patterns instead of random problem solving.

Today's focus was again on the Sliding Window pattern.

Problem solved:

✅ Number of Substrings Containing All Three Characters (LeetCode 1358)

Key idea:

The task was to count substrings that contain all three characters: a, b, and c.

Using a variable sliding window, I tracked the frequency of characters in the window.

Whenever the window contained at least one 'a', 'b', and 'c', every substring extending from the current left pointer to the end of the string would also satisfy the condition.

This allowed counting multiple substrings efficiently instead of checking each one individually.

What I learned

• Sliding window can also be used for counting problems, not just longest/shortest subarrays.
• Understanding how many valid substrings can be formed from a valid window is a powerful trick.
• Patterns make complex problems feel much simpler.

